</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Fatty liver disease is the most common cause of chronic liver disease in the United States. Noninvasive detection and quantification of fat is becoming more and more important clinically, due in large part to the growing prevalence of nonalcoholic fatty liver disease. Steatosis, the accumulation of fat-containing vacuoles within hepatocytes, is a key histologic feature of fatty liver disease. Liver biopsy, the current standard of reference for the assessment of steatosis, is invasive, has sampling errors, and is not appropriate in some settings. Several magnetic resonance (MR) imaging–based techniques—including chemical shift imaging, frequency-selective imaging, and MR spectroscopy—are currently in clinical use for the detection and quantification of fat-water admixtures, with each technique having important advantages, disadvantages, and limitations. These techniques permit the breakdown of the net MR signal into fat and water signal components, allowing the quantification of fat in liver tissue, and are increasingly being used in the diagnosis, treatment, and follow-up of fatty liver disease.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2009</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.291075123">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.291075123">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g01x.jpeg" height="1092" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1.</b>  Graph illustrates a simplified MR imaging spectrum of a fat-water admixture. The x axis represents the chemical shift, and the y axis represents signal intensity in arbitrary units <i>(a.u.)</i>. By convention, chemical shift values increase as one moves to the left on the x axis. If rounding errors are taken into consideration, the chemical shift of the proton signal in water <i>(H</i><sub>2</sub><i>O)</i> (4.7 ppm) is approximately 3.5 ppm greater than that of the proton signal in fat (1.3 ppm), CH<sub>2</sub> being the most abundant chemical moiety in fatty acids. That is, the water signal precesses faster than the fat signal by about 3.5 ppm. Again, by convention, the resonance frequency of a reference molecule, tetramethylsilane, is assigned a chemical shift of 0.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18c02x.jpeg" height="709" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2.</b>  Schematic illustrates chemical shift misregistration. Fat magnetization precesses slower than water magnetization, causing displacement of the fat signal toward a lower frequency along the frequency-encoding gradient.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g03a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1426" aria-labelledby="F3A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3a.</b>  Use of first-kind chemical shift in a 56-year-old man with histologically confirmed severe fatty liver disease. MR images obtained in an anteroposterior frequency-encoding direction <b>(a)</b> and a left-to-right frequency-encoding direction <b>(b)</b> show chemical shift misregistration bands (arrows) at the interface between the fatty liver parenchyma (high fat content) and portal triads (absent fat). The orientation of the bands depends on the frequency-encoding direction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F3A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g03b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1428" aria-labelledby="F3B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3b.</b>  Use of first-kind chemical shift in a 56-year-old man with histologically confirmed severe fatty liver disease. MR images obtained in an anteroposterior frequency-encoding direction <b>(a)</b> and a left-to-right frequency-encoding direction <b>(b)</b> show chemical shift misregistration bands (arrows) at the interface between the fatty liver parenchyma (high fat content) and portal triads (absent fat). The orientation of the bands depends on the frequency-encoding direction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F3B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g04a.jpeg" height="1425" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4a.</b>  Use of first-kind chemical shift in a 33-year-old woman with an ovarian dermoid cyst. <b>(a)</b> Oblique axial T1-weighted MR image shows an adnexal mass (arrow) with high- and low-signal components. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows chemical shift misregistration bands (arrow) traversing the mass, findings that suggest the presence of intralesional fat-water interfaces and are consistent with a dermoid cyst. <b>(c)</b> Axial fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image helps confirm the diagnosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F4A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g04b.jpeg" height="1645" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4b.</b>  Use of first-kind chemical shift in a 33-year-old woman with an ovarian dermoid cyst. <b>(a)</b> Oblique axial T1-weighted MR image shows an adnexal mass (arrow) with high- and low-signal components. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows chemical shift misregistration bands (arrow) traversing the mass, findings that suggest the presence of intralesional fat-water interfaces and are consistent with a dermoid cyst. <b>(c)</b> Axial fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image helps confirm the diagnosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F4B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g04c.jpeg" height="1536" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4c.</b>  Use of first-kind chemical shift in a 33-year-old woman with an ovarian dermoid cyst. <b>(a)</b> Oblique axial T1-weighted MR image shows an adnexal mass (arrow) with high- and low-signal components. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows chemical shift misregistration bands (arrow) traversing the mass, findings that suggest the presence of intralesional fat-water interfaces and are consistent with a dermoid cyst. <b>(c)</b> Axial fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image helps confirm the diagnosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F4C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g05a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1769" aria-labelledby="F5A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5a.</b>  Use of second-kind chemical shift in a 46-year-old woman with an adrenal adenoma. In-phase <b>(a)</b> and out-of-phase <b>(b)</b> GRE MR images show a right adrenal adenoma (arrow) and a fatty liver. The adenoma and liver both demonstrate loss of signal intensity on the out-of-phase image compared with the in-phase image, findings that indicate the presence of a fat-water admixture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F5A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g05b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1750" aria-labelledby="F5B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5b.</b>  Use of second-kind chemical shift in a 46-year-old woman with an adrenal adenoma. In-phase <b>(a)</b> and out-of-phase <b>(b)</b> GRE MR images show a right adrenal adenoma (arrow) and a fatty liver. The adenoma and liver both demonstrate loss of signal intensity on the out-of-phase image compared with the in-phase image, findings that indicate the presence of a fat-water admixture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F5B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g06a.jpeg" height="1268" width="1710" aria-labelledby="F6A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6a.</b>  Use of second-kind chemical shift in a 41-year-old man with focal pancreatic fat. <b>(a, b)</b> Unenhanced computed tomographic (CT) scan <b>(a)</b> and contrast material–enhanced MR image <b>(b)</b> of the abdomen show a hypoenhancing area within the uncinate process of the pancreas (arrow), a finding that is suspicious for neoplasm. <b>(c, d)</b> In-phase <b>(c)</b> and out-of-phase <b>(d)</b> MR images of the pancreas also show the hypoenhancing area (arrow) and help confirm that this finding represents focal fat deposition.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F6A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g06b.jpeg" height="1334" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6b.</b>  Use of second-kind chemical shift in a 41-year-old man with focal pancreatic fat. <b>(a, b)</b> Unenhanced computed tomographic (CT) scan <b>(a)</b> and contrast material–enhanced MR image <b>(b)</b> of the abdomen show a hypoenhancing area within the uncinate process of the pancreas (arrow), a finding that is suspicious for neoplasm. <b>(c, d)</b> In-phase <b>(c)</b> and out-of-phase <b>(d)</b> MR images of the pancreas also show the hypoenhancing area (arrow) and help confirm that this finding represents focal fat deposition.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F6B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g06c.jpeg" height="1343" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6c.</b>  Use of second-kind chemical shift in a 41-year-old man with focal pancreatic fat. <b>(a, b)</b> Unenhanced computed tomographic (CT) scan <b>(a)</b> and contrast material–enhanced MR image <b>(b)</b> of the abdomen show a hypoenhancing area within the uncinate process of the pancreas (arrow), a finding that is suspicious for neoplasm. <b>(c, d)</b> In-phase <b>(c)</b> and out-of-phase <b>(d)</b> MR images of the pancreas also show the hypoenhancing area (arrow) and help confirm that this finding represents focal fat deposition.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F6C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g06d.jpeg" height="1342" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6d.</b>  Use of second-kind chemical shift in a 41-year-old man with focal pancreatic fat. <b>(a, b)</b> Unenhanced computed tomographic (CT) scan <b>(a)</b> and contrast material–enhanced MR image <b>(b)</b> of the abdomen show a hypoenhancing area within the uncinate process of the pancreas (arrow), a finding that is suspicious for neoplasm. <b>(c, d)</b> In-phase <b>(c)</b> and out-of-phase <b>(d)</b> MR images of the pancreas also show the hypoenhancing area (arrow) and help confirm that this finding represents focal fat deposition.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F6D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g07a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1244" aria-labelledby="F7A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7a.</b>  Use of second-kind chemical shift in a 48-year-old woman with breast cancer. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows focal fat deposits mimicking metastases (arrows). The lesions were not visible at contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR imaging and demonstrated nonspecific high signal intensity at T2-weighted imaging. <b>(b)</b> In-phase MR image shows the lesions with increased T1 signal intensity (arrows). <b>(c)</b> On an out-of-phase MR image, the lesions show decreased signal intensity (arrows), a finding that helps confirm the presence of fat-water admixtures.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F7A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g07b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1288" aria-labelledby="F7B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7b.</b>  Use of second-kind chemical shift in a 48-year-old woman with breast cancer. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows focal fat deposits mimicking metastases (arrows). The lesions were not visible at contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR imaging and demonstrated nonspecific high signal intensity at T2-weighted imaging. <b>(b)</b> In-phase MR image shows the lesions with increased T1 signal intensity (arrows). <b>(c)</b> On an out-of-phase MR image, the lesions show decreased signal intensity (arrows), a finding that helps confirm the presence of fat-water admixtures.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F7B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g07c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1302" aria-labelledby="F7C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7c.</b>  Use of second-kind chemical shift in a 48-year-old woman with breast cancer. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows focal fat deposits mimicking metastases (arrows). The lesions were not visible at contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR imaging and demonstrated nonspecific high signal intensity at T2-weighted imaging. <b>(b)</b> In-phase MR image shows the lesions with increased T1 signal intensity (arrows). <b>(c)</b> On an out-of-phase MR image, the lesions show decreased signal intensity (arrows), a finding that helps confirm the presence of fat-water admixtures.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F7C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18c08x.jpeg" height="370" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8.</b>  Schematic illustrates India ink artifact. On an out-of-phase image, voxels at the interface between fatty and nonfatty tissues appear black because of near-complete cancellation of fat and water signals.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g09a.jpeg" height="1322" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9a.</b>  Frequency-selective fat saturation in a 52-year-old man with renal angiomyolipoma. T1-weighted MR images obtained without <b>(a)</b> and with <b>(b)</b> fat saturation show a right renal angiomyolipoma (arrow). The lesion shows decreased signal intensity on the fat-saturated image. Note also the saturation of the perirenal fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F9A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g09b.jpeg" height="1304" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9b.</b>  Frequency-selective fat saturation in a 52-year-old man with renal angiomyolipoma. T1-weighted MR images obtained without <b>(a)</b> and with <b>(b)</b> fat saturation show a right renal angiomyolipoma (arrow). The lesion shows decreased signal intensity on the fat-saturated image. Note also the saturation of the perirenal fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F9B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g10a.jpeg" height="1058" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10a.</b>  Magnetic field inhomogeneity in a 62-year-old man with bladder cancer and bilateral total hip replacements. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows severe degradation caused by beam-hardening artifact. <b>(b)</b> Non-fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image shows susceptibility artifact around the hip joints, but pelvic structures are well seen. Thin arrow indicates perivesicular fat; thick arrow indicates thick-walled bladder. <b>(c)</b> Fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image shows saturation of the perivesicular fat (thin arrow) but not of the bladder (thick arrow). This occurred because the actual B<sub>0</sub> at the tissue level differed from the presumed B<sub>0</sub> due to magnetic field inhomogeneity induced by the metallic hip prostheses, leading to inadvertent suppression of the water signal.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F10A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g10b.jpeg" height="1082" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10b.</b>  Magnetic field inhomogeneity in a 62-year-old man with bladder cancer and bilateral total hip replacements. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows severe degradation caused by beam-hardening artifact. <b>(b)</b> Non-fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image shows susceptibility artifact around the hip joints, but pelvic structures are well seen. Thin arrow indicates perivesicular fat; thick arrow indicates thick-walled bladder. <b>(c)</b> Fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image shows saturation of the perivesicular fat (thin arrow) but not of the bladder (thick arrow). This occurred because the actual B<sub>0</sub> at the tissue level differed from the presumed B<sub>0</sub> due to magnetic field inhomogeneity induced by the metallic hip prostheses, leading to inadvertent suppression of the water signal.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F10B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g10c.jpeg" height="1061" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10c.</b>  Magnetic field inhomogeneity in a 62-year-old man with bladder cancer and bilateral total hip replacements. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows severe degradation caused by beam-hardening artifact. <b>(b)</b> Non-fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image shows susceptibility artifact around the hip joints, but pelvic structures are well seen. Thin arrow indicates perivesicular fat; thick arrow indicates thick-walled bladder. <b>(c)</b> Fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image shows saturation of the perivesicular fat (thin arrow) but not of the bladder (thick arrow). This occurred because the actual B<sub>0</sub> at the tissue level differed from the presumed B<sub>0</sub> due to magnetic field inhomogeneity induced by the metallic hip prostheses, leading to inadvertent suppression of the water signal.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F10C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g11a.jpeg" height="1504" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11a.</b>  Characteristic frequencies of water signal and fat signal at MR spectroscopy. <b>(a)</b> On an MR spectroscopic image, a 3 × 3 × 3-cm voxel (box) has been placed within the liver. <b>(b)</b> Graph illustrates signal intensity (in arbitrary units) (y axis) as a function of pre-cessional frequency (in parts per million) (x axis). The graph shows water and fat signals with their characteristic frequencies (4.7 ppm and 1.3 ppm, respectively).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F11A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g11b.jpeg" height="1610" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11b.</b>  Characteristic frequencies of water signal and fat signal at MR spectroscopy. <b>(a)</b> On an MR spectroscopic image, a 3 × 3 × 3-cm voxel (box) has been placed within the liver. <b>(b)</b> Graph illustrates signal intensity (in arbitrary units) (y axis) as a function of precessional frequency (in parts per million) (x axis). The graph shows water and fat signals with their characteristic frequencies (4.7 ppm and 1.3 ppm, respectively).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F11B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g12a.jpeg" height="1154" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F12A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12a.</b>  Calculation of FSF in a 58-year-old man with severe fatty liver disease. <b>(a, b)</b> Out-of-phase <b>(a)</b> and in-phase <b>(b)</b> MR images obtained at 1.5 T show a fatty liver with a focal area of fat sparing (arrow). <i>S</i> = signal intensity in a region of interest (circle) placed over the liver. Cancellation of fat and water signals causes diffuse signal intensity loss on the out-of-phase image. <b>(c)</b> FSF map. Fat-water admixture (fatty liver) appears bright, whereas subcutaneous fat (almost exclusively fat) appears similar to lean tissue (eg, spleen) due to fat-water dominance ambiguity. Arrow = focal area of fat sparing. FSF can be estimated by measuring the liver signal on the FSF map (33% in this case). If no FSF map is available, FSF can be calculated with Equation 5; in this case, (256 − 87) ÷ (2 × 256) = 33%.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F12A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g12b.jpeg" height="1143" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F12B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12b.</b>  Calculation of FSF in a 58-year-old man with severe fatty liver disease. <b>(a, b)</b> Out-of-phase <b>(a)</b> and in-phase <b>(b)</b> MR images obtained at 1.5 T show a fatty liver with a focal area of fat sparing (arrow). <i>S</i> = signal intensity in a region of interest (circle) placed over the liver. Cancellation of fat and water signals causes diffuse signal intensity loss on the out-of-phase image. <b>(c)</b> FSF map. Fat-water admixture (fatty liver) appears bright, whereas subcutaneous fat (almost exclusively fat) appears similar to lean tissue (eg, spleen) due to fat-water dominance ambiguity. Arrow = focal area of fat sparing. FSF can be estimated by measuring the liver signal on the FSF map (33% in this case). If no FSF map is available, FSF can be calculated with Equation 5; in this case, (256 − 87) ÷ (2 × 256) = 33%.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F12B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g12c.jpeg" height="1192" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F12C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12c.</b>  Calculation of FSF in a 58-year-old man with severe fatty liver disease. <b>(a, b)</b> Out-of-phase <b>(a)</b> and in-phase <b>(b)</b> MR images obtained at 1.5 T show a fatty liver with a focal area of fat sparing (arrow). <i>S</i> = signal intensity in a region of interest (circle) placed over the liver. Cancellation of fat and water signals causes diffuse signal intensity loss on the out-of-phase image. <b>(c)</b> FSF map. Fat-water admixture (fatty liver) appears bright, whereas subcutaneous fat (almost exclusively fat) appears similar to lean tissue (eg, spleen) due to fat-water dominance ambiguity. Arrow = focal area of fat sparing. FSF can be estimated by measuring the liver signal on the FSF map (33% in this case). If no FSF map is available, FSF can be calculated with Equation 5; in this case, (256 − 87) ÷ (2 × 256) = 33%.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F12C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g13x.jpeg" height="1220" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13.</b>  Graph illustrates the MR imaging spectrum of a fatty human liver. Water <i>(H</i><sub>2</sub><i>O)</i> protons resonate at 4.7 ppm and fat <i>(CH</i><sub>2</sub><i>)</i> protons at 1.3 ppm. Other constituents of triglycerides (eg, CH<sub>3</sub>, CH<sub>2</sub>-COOR moieties <i>[others]</i>, and CH = CH) have their own characteristic resonance frequencies at 0.9, 2.1, and 5.3 ppm, respectively.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g14a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1333" aria-labelledby="F14A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14a.</b>  Fat quantification with frequency-selective imaging in a 66-year-old woman with histologically confirmed nonalcoholic fatty liver disease. <b>(a, b)</b> Single-shot fast spin-echo (FSE) images obtained without <b>(a)</b> and with <b>(b)</b> fat saturation show both fat and water signal <b>(a)</b> and water signal only <b>(b). (c)</b> Image obtained by subtracting <b>b</b> from <b>a</b> shows fat signal only. <b>(d)</b> On an FSF map that was also calculated from <b>a</b> and <b>b</b> (with use of Eq 6), the liver is gray (moderate amount of fat), subcutaneous fat is white (mostly fat), and cerebrospinal fluid is black (no fat). Estimated FSF was 12%–15%, depending on the exact region of interest in the liver. FSF estimated with single-voxel MR spectroscopy was 13.6%.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F14A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g14b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1355" aria-labelledby="F14B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14b.</b>  Fat quantification with frequency-selective imaging in a 66-year-old woman with histologically confirmed nonalcoholic fatty liver disease. <b>(a, b)</b> Single-shot fast spin-echo (FSE) images obtained without <b>(a)</b> and with <b>(b)</b> fat saturation show both fat and water signal <b>(a)</b> and water signal only <b>(b). (c)</b> Image obtained by subtracting <b>b</b> from <b>a</b> shows fat signal only. <b>(d)</b> On an FSF map that was also calculated from <b>a</b> and <b>b</b> (with use of Eq 6), the liver is gray (moderate amount of fat), subcutaneous fat is white (mostly fat), and cerebrospinal fluid is black (no fat). Estimated FSF was 12%–15%, depending on the exact region of interest in the liver. FSF estimated with single-voxel MR spectroscopy was 13.6%.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F14B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g14c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1327" aria-labelledby="F14C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14c.</b>  Fat quantification with frequency-selective imaging in a 66-year-old woman with histologically confirmed nonalcoholic fatty liver disease. <b>(a, b)</b> Single-shot fast spin-echo (FSE) images obtained without <b>(a)</b> and with <b>(b)</b> fat saturation show both fat and water signal <b>(a)</b> and water signal only <b>(b). (c)</b> Image obtained by subtracting <b>b</b> from <b>a</b> shows fat signal only. <b>(d)</b> On an FSF map that was also calculated from <b>a</b> and <b>b</b> (with use of Eq 6), the liver is gray (moderate amount of fat), subcutaneous fat is white (mostly fat), and cerebrospinal fluid is black (no fat). Estimated FSF was 12%–15%, depending on the exact region of interest in the liver. FSF estimated with single-voxel MR spectroscopy was 13.6%.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F14C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g14d.jpeg" height="1800" width="1335" aria-labelledby="F14D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14d.</b>  Fat quantification with frequency-selective imaging in a 66-year-old woman with histologically confirmed nonalcoholic fatty liver disease. <b>(a, b)</b> Single-shot fast spin-echo (FSE) images obtained without <b>(a)</b> and with <b>(b)</b> fat saturation show both fat and water signal <b>(a)</b> and water signal only <b>(b). (c)</b> Image obtained by subtracting <b>b</b> from <b>a</b> shows fat signal only. <b>(d)</b> On an FSF map that was also calculated from <b>a</b> and <b>b</b> (with use of Eq 6), the liver is gray (moderate amount of fat), subcutaneous fat is white (mostly fat), and cerebrospinal fluid is black (no fat). Estimated FSF was 12%–15%, depending on the exact region of interest in the liver. FSF estimated with single-voxel MR spectroscopy was 13.6%.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F14D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18c15x.jpeg" height="932" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15.</b>  Schematic illustrates fat-water MR imaging. An imaging voxel contains both fat and water molecules. The signal of fat or water is proportional to the proton density <i>(PD)</i> within the voxel but is modified by relaxation effects. T1 and T2 (or T2<b>*</b>) relaxation effects are functions of the chemical properties of fat or water molecules and are modified with the choice of imaging parameters. For fat detection, relative amplification of the “fat pathway,” achieved by choosing certain imaging parameters, improves detection sensitivity. For fat quantification, relaxation effects should be minimized, so that both pathways are balanced; this can be achieved with certain imaging parameters, modeling of relaxation effects, or use of contrast agents. Chemical properties are usually fixed, unless contrast agents are used.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g16a.jpeg" height="1117" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F16A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16a.</b>  Effect of T1 weighting on the relative signal intensities of fatty and nonfatty tissues in the same patient as in <a href="#F12A">Figure 12</a>. <b>(a, b)</b> In-phase MR images (echo time = 4.6 msec) show how subcutaneous adipose tissue, visceral adipose tissue, and fatty liver have higher signal intensity relative to the spleen with heavy T1 weighting (flip angle = 90°) <b>(a)</b> than with minimal T1 weighting (flip angle = 15°) <b>(b)</b>. Heavy T1 weighting could also be achieved with a low repetition time (eg, 50 msec), whereas a higher repetition time (eg, 500 msec) would provide minimally T1-weighted images. <b>(c, d)</b> Out-of-phase MR images (echo time = 2.3 msec) show how signal loss in a fatty liver (water-dominant tissue) is more pronounced and the estimated fat fraction greater with heavy T1 weighting <b>(c)</b> than with minimal T1 weighting <b>(d)</b>. In contrast, signal loss in subcutaneous and visceral adipose tissue (fat-dominant tissues) is greater with minimal T1 weighting.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F16A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g16b.jpeg" height="1118" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F16B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16b.</b>  Effect of T1 weighting on the relative signal intensities of fatty and nonfatty tissues in the same patient as in <a href="#F12A">Figure 12</a>. <b>(a, b)</b> In-phase MR images (echo time = 4.6 msec) show how subcutaneous adipose tissue, visceral adipose tissue, and fatty liver have higher signal intensity relative to the spleen with heavy T1 weighting (flip angle = 90°) <b>(a)</b> than with minimal T1 weighting (flip angle = 15°) <b>(b)</b>. Heavy T1 weighting could also be achieved with a low repetition time (eg, 50 msec), whereas a higher repetition time (eg, 500 msec) would provide minimally T1-weighted images. <b>(c, d)</b> Out-of-phase MR images (echo time = 2.3 msec) show how signal loss in a fatty liver (water-dominant tissue) is more pronounced and the estimated fat fraction greater with heavy T1 weighting <b>(c)</b> than with minimal T1 weighting <b>(d)</b>. In contrast, signal loss in subcutaneous and visceral adipose tissue (fat-dominant tissues) is greater with minimal T1 weighting.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F16B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g16c.jpeg" height="1111" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F16C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16c.</b>  Effect of T1 weighting on the relative signal intensities of fatty and nonfatty tissues in the same patient as in <a href="#F12A">Figure 12</a>. <b>(a, b)</b> In-phase MR images (echo time = 4.6 msec) show how subcutaneous adipose tissue, visceral adipose tissue, and fatty liver have higher signal intensity relative to the spleen with heavy T1 weighting (flip angle = 90°) <b>(a)</b> than with minimal T1 weighting (flip angle = 15°) <b>(b)</b>. Heavy T1 weighting could also be achieved with a low repetition time (eg, 50 msec), whereas a higher repetition time (eg, 500 msec) would provide minimally T1-weighted images. <b>(c, d)</b> Out-of-phase MR images (echo time = 2.3 msec) show how signal loss in a fatty liver (water-dominant tissue) is more pronounced and the estimated fat fraction greater with heavy T1 weighting <b>(c)</b> than with minimal T1 weighting <b>(d)</b>. In contrast, signal loss in subcutaneous and visceral adipose tissue (fat-dominant tissues) is greater with minimal T1 weighting.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F16C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g16d.jpeg" height="1112" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F16D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16d.</b>  Effect of T1 weighting on the relative signal intensities of fatty and nonfatty tissues in the same patient as in <a href="#F12A">Figure 12</a>. <b>(a, b)</b> In-phase MR images (echo time = 4.6 msec) show how subcutaneous adipose tissue, visceral adipose tissue, and fatty liver have higher signal intensity relative to the spleen with heavy T1 weighting (flip angle = 90°) <b>(a)</b> than with minimal T1 weighting (flip angle = 15°) <b>(b)</b>. Heavy T1 weighting could also be achieved with a low repetition time (eg, 50 msec), whereas a higher repetition time (eg, 500 msec) would provide minimally T1-weighted images. <b>(c, d)</b> Out-of-phase MR images (echo time = 2.3 msec) show how signal loss in a fatty liver (water-dominant tissue) is more pronounced and the estimated fat fraction greater with heavy T1 weighting <b>(c)</b> than with minimal T1 weighting <b>(d)</b>. In contrast, signal loss in subcutaneous and visceral adipose tissue (fat-dominant tissues) is greater with minimal T1 weighting.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F16D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g17x.jpeg" height="1314" width="1183" aria-labelledby="F17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17.</b>  Resolution of fat-water ambiguity in a 61-year-old man with an adrenal adenoma. In-phase (left) and out-of-phase (right) MR images obtained with flip angles <i>(FA)</i> of 90° (top) and 20° (bottom) show a right adrenal adenoma (arrow). The signal cancellation on the out-of-phase images is more dramatic with a high flip angle (top right) than with a lower flip angle (bottom right), a finding that confirms that the adrenal lesion is a water-dominant admixture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g18x.jpeg" height="1656" width="1441" aria-labelledby="F18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18.</b>  Resolution of fat-water ambiguity in a 52-year-old man with a renal angiomyolipoma. In-phase (left) and out-of-phase (right) MR images obtained with flip angles <i>(FA)</i> of 90° (top) and 20° (bottom) show a right renal angiomyolipoma (arrow). The signal cancellation on the out-of-phase images is more dramatic with a low flip angle (bottom right) than with a high flip angle (top right), a finding that confirms that the angiomyolipoma is a fat-dominant admixture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g19x.jpeg" height="1314" width="1153" aria-labelledby="F19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19.</b>  Resolution of fat-water ambiguity achieved with gadolinium <i>(Gd)</i> administration and a 90° flip angle <i>(FA).</i> Gadolinium-enhanced in-phase (left) and out-of-phase (right) MR images obtained in the same patient as in <a href="#F17">Figure 17</a> show the right adrenal adenoma (arrow). Signal dropout in the adenoma is greater on the precontrast out-of-phase image (top right) than on the postcontrast out-of-phase image (bottom right), a finding that confirms that the adrenal lesion contains a fat-water admixture with water as the dominant component.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g20x.jpeg" height="1152" width="1494" aria-labelledby="F20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 20.</b>  Subcutaneous edema (wet fat) in a patient with hypoalbuminemia. Gadolinium-enhanced in-phase (left) and out-of-phase (right) MR images show edema in the subcutaneous fat (arrow). Signal dropout is greater on the postcontrast out-of-phase image (bottom right) than on the precontrast out-of-phase image (top right), a finding that confirms that the subcutaneous edema contains a fat-water admixture with fat as the dominant component.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g21x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1769" aria-labelledby="F21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21.</b>  Graph illustrates GRE MR signal intensity in arbitrary units <i>(a.u.)</i> from fatty liver (~25% at MR spectroscopy) as a function of echo time <i>(TE)</i> at 1.5 T. A “best fit” biexponential curve has been drawn through measured in-phase <i>(IP)</i> and out-of-phase <i>(OP)</i> signal intensities and shows both phase interference effect between fat and water protons and T2<b>*</b> decay.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g22a.jpeg" height="1159" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F22A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22a.</b>  Underestimation of the fat signal in a 69-year-old woman with a severely iron-overloaded, mildly steatotic liver. <b>(a–f)</b> Serial low-flip-angle GRE out-of-phase (<b>a</b>, <b>c</b>, and <b>e</b>) and in-phase (<b>b</b>, <b>d</b>, and <b>f</b>) images obtained at echo times of 2.3 <b>(a)</b>, 4.6 <b>(b)</b>, 6.9 <b>(c)</b>, 9.2 <b>(d)</b>, 11.5 <b>(e)</b>, and 13.8 <b>(f)</b> msec at 1.5 T show progressive loss of liver parenchyma signal as echo time lengthens owing to T2<b>*</b> effects caused by excess liver iron, which conceals the phase interference of fat and water protons in the liver fat. <b>(g)</b> On a T2<b>*</b> uncorrected FSF map obtained from just two echoes (out-of-phase, then in-phase), the amount of fat present is grossly underestimated. <b>(h)</b> T2<b>*</b>-corrected FSF map obtained by fitting the multiecho data to the biexponential model (see Appendix) corrects for the short T2<b>*</b> of the underlying liver and allows quantification of the diffuse fat deposition (~5%).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F22A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g22b.jpeg" height="1160" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F22B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22b.</b>  Underestimation of the fat signal in a 69-year-old woman with a severely iron-overloaded, mildly steatotic liver. <b>(a–f)</b> Serial low-flip-angle GRE out-of-phase (<b>a</b>, <b>c</b>, and <b>e</b>) and in-phase (<b>b</b>, <b>d</b>, and <b>f</b>) images obtained at echo times of 2.3 <b>(a)</b>, 4.6 <b>(b)</b>, 6.9 <b>(c)</b>, 9.2 <b>(d)</b>, 11.5 <b>(e)</b>, and 13.8 <b>(f)</b> msec at 1.5 T show progressive loss of liver parenchyma signal as echo time lengthens owing to T2<b>*</b> effects caused by excess liver iron, which conceals the phase interference of fat and water protons in the liver fat. <b>(g)</b> On a T2<b>*</b> uncorrected FSF map obtained from just two echoes (out-of-phase, then in-phase), the amount of fat present is grossly underestimated. <b>(h)</b> T2<b>*</b>-corrected FSF map obtained by fitting the multiecho data to the biexponential model (see Appendix) corrects for the short T2<b>*</b> of the underlying liver and allows quantification of the diffuse fat deposition (~5%).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F22B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g22c.jpeg" height="1159" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F22C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22c.</b>  Underestimation of the fat signal in a 69-year-old woman with a severely iron-overloaded, mildly steatotic liver. <b>(a–f)</b> Serial low-flip-angle GRE out-of-phase (<b>a</b>, <b>c</b>, and <b>e</b>) and in-phase (<b>b</b>, <b>d</b>, and <b>f</b>) images obtained at echo times of 2.3 <b>(a)</b>, 4.6 <b>(b)</b>, 6.9 <b>(c)</b>, 9.2 <b>(d)</b>, 11.5 <b>(e)</b>, and 13.8 <b>(f)</b> msec at 1.5 T show progressive loss of liver parenchyma signal as echo time lengthens owing to T2<b>*</b> effects caused by excess liver iron, which conceals the phase interference of fat and water protons in the liver fat. <b>(g)</b> On a T2<b>*</b> uncorrected FSF map obtained from just two echoes (out-of-phase, then in-phase), the amount of fat present is grossly underestimated. <b>(h)</b> T2<b>*</b>-corrected FSF map obtained by fitting the multiecho data to the biexponential model (see Appendix) corrects for the short T2<b>*</b> of the underlying liver and allows quantification of the diffuse fat deposition (~5%).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F22C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g22d.jpeg" height="1160" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F22D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22d.</b>  Underestimation of the fat signal in a 69-year-old woman with a severely iron-overloaded, mildly steatotic liver. <b>(a–f)</b> Serial low-flip-angle GRE out-of-phase (<b>a</b>, <b>c</b>, and <b>e</b>) and in-phase (<b>b</b>, <b>d</b>, and <b>f</b>) images obtained at echo times of 2.3 <b>(a)</b>, 4.6 <b>(b)</b>, 6.9 <b>(c)</b>, 9.2 <b>(d)</b>, 11.5 <b>(e)</b>, and 13.8 <b>(f)</b> msec at 1.5 T show progressive loss of liver parenchyma signal as echo time lengthens owing to T2<b>*</b> effects caused by excess liver iron, which conceals the phase interference of fat and water protons in the liver fat. <b>(g)</b> On a T2<b>*</b> uncorrected FSF map obtained from just two echoes (out-of-phase, then in-phase), the amount of fat present is grossly underestimated. <b>(h)</b> T2<b>*</b>-corrected FSF map obtained by fitting the multiecho data to the biexponential model (see Appendix) corrects for the short T2<b>*</b> of the underlying liver and allows quantification of the diffuse fat deposition (~5%).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F22D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g22e.jpeg" height="1159" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F22E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22e.</b>  Underestimation of the fat signal in a 69-year-old woman with a severely iron-overloaded, mildly steatotic liver. <b>(a–f)</b> Serial low-flip-angle GRE out-of-phase (<b>a</b>, <b>c</b>, and <b>e</b>) and in-phase (<b>b</b>, <b>d</b>, and <b>f</b>) images obtained at echo times of 2.3 <b>(a)</b>, 4.6 <b>(b)</b>, 6.9 <b>(c)</b>, 9.2 <b>(d)</b>, 11.5 <b>(e)</b>, and 13.8 <b>(f)</b> msec at 1.5 T show progressive loss of liver parenchyma signal as echo time lengthens owing to T2<b>*</b> effects caused by excess liver iron, which conceals the phase interference of fat and water protons in the liver fat. <b>(g)</b> On a T2<b>*</b> uncorrected FSF map obtained from just two echoes (out-of-phase, then in-phase), the amount of fat present is grossly underestimated. <b>(h)</b> T2<b>*</b>-corrected FSF map obtained by fitting the multiecho data to the biexponential model (see Appendix) corrects for the short T2<b>*</b> of the underlying liver and allows quantification of the diffuse fat deposition (~5%).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F22E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22F" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g22f.jpeg" height="1160" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F22F" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22f.</b>  Underestimation of the fat signal in a 69-year-old woman with a severely iron-overloaded, mildly steatotic liver. <b>(a–f)</b> Serial low-flip-angle GRE out-of-phase (<b>a</b>, <b>c</b>, and <b>e</b>) and in-phase (<b>b</b>, <b>d</b>, and <b>f</b>) images obtained at echo times of 2.3 <b>(a)</b>, 4.6 <b>(b)</b>, 6.9 <b>(c)</b>, 9.2 <b>(d)</b>, 11.5 <b>(e)</b>, and 13.8 <b>(f)</b> msec at 1.5 T show progressive loss of liver parenchyma signal as echo time lengthens owing to T2<b>*</b> effects caused by excess liver iron, which conceals the phase interference of fat and water protons in the liver fat. <b>(g)</b> On a T2<b>*</b> uncorrected FSF map obtained from just two echoes (out-of-phase, then in-phase), the amount of fat present is grossly underestimated. <b>(h)</b> T2<b>*</b>-corrected FSF map obtained by fitting the multiecho data to the biexponential model (see Appendix) corrects for the short T2<b>*</b> of the underlying liver and allows quantification of the diffuse fat deposition (~5%).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F22F">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22G" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g22g.jpeg" height="1257" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F22G" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22g.</b>  Underestimation of the fat signal in a 69-year-old woman with a severely iron-overloaded, mildly steatotic liver. <b>(a–f)</b> Serial low-flip-angle GRE out-of-phase (<b>a</b>, <b>c</b>, and <b>e</b>) and in-phase (<b>b</b>, <b>d</b>, and <b>f</b>) images obtained at echo times of 2.3 <b>(a)</b>, 4.6 <b>(b)</b>, 6.9 <b>(c)</b>, 9.2 <b>(d)</b>, 11.5 <b>(e)</b>, and 13.8 <b>(f)</b> msec at 1.5 T show progressive loss of liver parenchyma signal as echo time lengthens owing to T2<b>*</b> effects caused by excess liver iron, which conceals the phase interference of fat and water protons in the liver fat. <b>(g)</b> On a T2<b>*</b> uncorrected FSF map obtained from just two echoes (out-of-phase, then in-phase), the amount of fat present is grossly underestimated. <b>(h)</b> T2<b>*</b>-corrected FSF map obtained by fitting the multiecho data to the biexponential model (see Appendix) corrects for the short T2<b>*</b> of the underlying liver and allows quantification of the diffuse fat deposition (~5%).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F22G">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22H" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g22h.jpeg" height="1258" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F22H" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22h.</b>  Underestimation of the fat signal in a 69-year-old woman with a severely iron-overloaded, mildly steatotic liver. <b>(a–f)</b> Serial low-flip-angle GRE out-of-phase (<b>a</b>, <b>c</b>, and <b>e</b>) and in-phase (<b>b</b>, <b>d</b>, and <b>f</b>) images obtained at echo times of 2.3 <b>(a)</b>, 4.6 <b>(b)</b>, 6.9 <b>(c)</b>, 9.2 <b>(d)</b>, 11.5 <b>(e)</b>, and 13.8 <b>(f)</b> msec at 1.5 T show progressive loss of liver parenchyma signal as echo time lengthens owing to T2<b>*</b> effects caused by excess liver iron, which conceals the phase interference of fat and water protons in the liver fat. <b>(g)</b> On a T2<b>*</b> uncorrected FSF map obtained from just two echoes (out-of-phase, then in-phase), the amount of fat present is grossly underestimated. <b>(h)</b> T2<b>*</b>-corrected FSF map obtained by fitting the multiecho data to the biexponential model (see Appendix) corrects for the short T2<b>*</b> of the underlying liver and allows quantification of the diffuse fat deposition (~5%).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F22H">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F23A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g23a.jpeg" height="1584" width="1478" aria-labelledby="F23A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 23a.</b>  Fat quantification with frequency-selective imaging. Boxes = areas of interest, percentages = fat fraction estimates. <b>(a, b)</b> FSF maps obtained with single-shot FSE imaging at 65 <b>(a)</b> and 32 <b>(b)</b> msec. <b>(c)</b> T2-corrected FSF map (<b>a</b> − <b>b</b>). Greater T2 weighting accentuates longer T2 signal, and the fat fraction is overestimated. <b>(d)</b> On a multiecho low-flip-angle chemical shift single-shot FSE T2<b>*</b>-corrected FSF map, dry fat appears similar to lean tissues due to fat-water dominance ambiguity. <span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-enun">If relaxation effects are minimized, different imaging techniques yield similar fat quantity estimates.</span><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F23A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F23B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g23b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1664" aria-labelledby="F23B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 23b.</b>  Fat quantification with frequency-selective imaging. Boxes = areas of interest, percentages = fat fraction estimates. <b>(a, b)</b> FSF maps obtained with single-shot FSE imaging at 65 <b>(a)</b> and 32 <b>(b)</b> msec. <b>(c)</b> T2-corrected FSF map (<b>a</b> − <b>b</b>). Greater T2 weighting accentuates longer T2 signal, and the fat fraction is overestimated. <b>(d)</b> On a multiecho low-flip-angle chemical shift single-shot FSE T2<b>*</b>-corrected FSF map, dry fat appears similar to lean tissues due to fat-water dominance ambiguity. <span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-enun">If relaxation effects are minimized, different imaging techniques yield similar fat quantity estimates.</span><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F23B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F23C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g23c.jpeg" height="1620" width="1501" aria-labelledby="F23C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 23c.</b>  Fat quantification with frequency-selective imaging. Boxes = areas of interest, percentages = fat fraction estimates. <b>(a, b)</b> FSF maps obtained with single-shot FSE imaging at 65 <b>(a)</b> and 32 <b>(b)</b> msec. <b>(c)</b> T2-corrected FSF map (<b>a</b> − <b>b</b>). Greater T2 weighting accentuates longer T2 signal, and the fat fraction is overestimated. <b>(d)</b> On a multiecho low-flip-angle chemical shift single-shot FSE T2<b>*</b>-corrected FSF map, dry fat appears similar to lean tissues due to fat-water dominance ambiguity. <span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-enun">If relaxation effects are minimized, different imaging techniques yield similar fat quantity estimates.</span><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F23C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F23D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18g23d.jpeg" height="1566" width="1459" aria-labelledby="F23D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 23d.</b>  Fat quantification with frequency-selective imaging. Boxes = areas of interest, percentages = fat fraction estimates. <b>(a, b)</b> FSF maps obtained with single-shot FSE imaging at 65 <b>(a)</b> and 32 <b>(b)</b> msec. <b>(c)</b> T2-corrected FSF map (<b>a</b> − <b>b</b>). Greater T2 weighting accentuates longer T2 signal, and the fat fraction is overestimated. <b>(d)</b> On a multiecho low-flip-angle chemical shift single-shot FSE T2<b>*</b>-corrected FSF map, dry fat appears similar to lean tissues due to fat-water dominance ambiguity. <span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-enun">If relaxation effects are minimized, different imaging techniques yield similar fat quantity estimates.</span><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F23D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F24A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18c24a.jpeg" height="1043" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F24A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 24a.</b>  Graphs illustrate the MR imaging spectra for a fatty liver obtained with echo times of 30 <b>(a)</b>, 40 <b>(b)</b>, 50 <b>(c)</b>, 60 <b>(d)</b>, and 70 <b>(e)</b> msec. The peak height decreases with increasing echo time due to T2 relaxation. Each peak has its own relaxation rate. The water peak decays faster than the fat peak, reflecting the shorter T2 of normal liver tissue compared with fat. Fat quantification at a single echo time is therefore biased by T2 relaxation effects, and peak-by-peak T2 correction is necessary for accurate and unbiased quantification.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F24A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F24B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18c24b.jpeg" height="1045" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F24B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 24b.</b>  Graphs illustrate the MR imaging spectra for a fatty liver obtained with echo times of 30 <b>(a)</b>, 40 <b>(b)</b>, 50 <b>(c)</b>, 60 <b>(d)</b>, and 70 <b>(e)</b> msec. The peak height decreases with increasing echo time due to T2 relaxation. Each peak has its own relaxation rate. The water peak decays faster than the fat peak, reflecting the shorter T2 of normal liver tissue compared with fat. Fat quantification at a single echo time is therefore biased by T2 relaxation effects, and peak-by-peak T2 correction is necessary for accurate and unbiased quantification.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F24B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F24C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18c24c.jpeg" height="1044" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F24C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 24c.</b>  Graphs illustrate the MR imaging spectra for a fatty liver obtained with echo times of 30 <b>(a)</b>, 40 <b>(b)</b>, 50 <b>(c)</b>, 60 <b>(d)</b>, and 70 <b>(e)</b> msec. The peak height decreases with increasing echo time due to T2 relaxation. Each peak has its own relaxation rate. The water peak decays faster than the fat peak, reflecting the shorter T2 of normal liver tissue compared with fat. Fat quantification at a single echo time is therefore biased by T2 relaxation effects, and peak-by-peak T2 correction is necessary for accurate and unbiased quantification.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F24C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F24D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18c24d.jpeg" height="1044" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F24D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 24d.</b>  Graphs illustrate the MR imaging spectra for a fatty liver obtained with echo times of 30 <b>(a)</b>, 40 <b>(b)</b>, 50 <b>(c)</b>, 60 <b>(d)</b>, and 70 <b>(e)</b> msec. The peak height decreases with increasing echo time due to T2 relaxation. Each peak has its own relaxation rate. The water peak decays faster than the fat peak, reflecting the shorter T2 of normal liver tissue compared with fat. Fat quantification at a single echo time is therefore biased by T2 relaxation effects, and peak-by-peak T2 correction is necessary for accurate and unbiased quantification.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F24D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F24E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18c24e.jpeg" height="1035" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F24E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 24e.</b>  Graphs illustrate the MR imaging spectra for a fatty liver obtained with echo times of 30 <b>(a)</b>, 40 <b>(b)</b>, 50 <b>(c)</b>, 60 <b>(d)</b>, and 70 <b>(e)</b> msec. The peak height decreases with increasing echo time due to T2 relaxation. Each peak has its own relaxation rate. The water peak decays faster than the fat peak, reflecting the shorter T2 of normal liver tissue compared with fat. Fat quantification at a single echo time is therefore biased by T2 relaxation effects, and peak-by-peak T2 correction is necessary for accurate and unbiased quantification.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F24E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F25" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18l25x.jpeg" height="816" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F25" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 25.</b>  Graph summarizes MR imaging fat detection and quantification techniques. Observed MR signal can be broken down into the water and fat signal components. The fat component can be further broken down into the signals from various chemical moieties. The three fundamental MR imaging techniques for fat assessment—chemical shift imaging <i>(CSI)</i>, frequency-selective imaging <i>(FSI)</i>, and MR spectroscopy <i>(MRS)</i>—make use of different strategies to separate the fat signal from the water signal. Once fat and water signals have been identified and their intensities measured, the fractional fat content (fat fraction) can be calculated as the ratio of the fat signal to the total MR signal. <i>FS</i> = fat-saturated, <i>IP</i> = in-phase, <i>NFS</i> = non-fat-saturated, <i>OP</i> = out-of-phase.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075123&amp;id=F25">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="T1" class="table"><figcaption><b>In-Phase and Out-of-Phase Echo Times for Different Magnetic Field Strengths</b></figcaption><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075123/asset/images/g09ja18t01x.jpeg" height="408" width="1800" aria-labelledby="T1" loading="lazy" /><div class="notes"><div role="doc-footnote"><div role="paragraph">Note.—The period τ of signal oscillation (in milliseconds) depends on the magnetic field strength (B<sub>0</sub>) and is given by the following formula:</div><div id="FD2" class="display-formula"><div class="equation" role="math"><div class="inner"><span class="core-tex">\[{\tau}\ =\ 1000\ msec/sec\ {\div}\ chemical\ shift\ (ppm)\ {\times}\ {\gamma}\ (MHz/T)\ {\times}\ B_{0}.\]</span></div></div></div><div role="paragraph">For a chemical shift of 3.5 ppm and γ = 42.58 MHz/T, the period of signal oscillation is 6.71 msec/B<sub>0</sub>. Thus, the oscillation period is 6.71 msec at 1.0 T, 4.47 msec at 1.5 T, and 2.24 msec at 3 T. For a given B<sub>0</sub>, the earliest echo time at which signals from fat and water are in phase is simply equal to the oscillation period specified in Equation 2, and the earliest echo time at which the signals are out of phase is one-half the oscillation period.</div></div></div></figure></div><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="R1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Szczepaniak</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">LS</span></span>, Nurenberg P, Leonard D, et al. Magnetic resonance spectroscopy to measure hepatic triglyceride content: prevalence of hepatic steatosis in the general population. <em>Am J Physiol Endocrinol Metab</em>2005; 288: E462–E468.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1152/ajpendo.00064.2004">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15339742/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Am+J+Physiol+Endocrinol+Metab&amp;publication_year=2005&amp;pages=E462&amp;doi=10.1152%2Fajpendo.00064.2004&amp;pmid=15339742">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="R2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Belfort</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">R</span></span>, Harrison SA, Brown K, et al. A placebo-controlled trial of pioglitazone in subjects with nonalcoholic steatohepatitis. <em>N Engl J Med</em>2006;